# Code Style, Testing & Git Conventions (server/)

## TypeScript

- `strict: true`, `noImplicitAny: true`, `noUncheckedIndexedAccess: true` in
  `server/tsconfig.json`.
- No `any`. Use `unknown` + narrowing, or a proper generic/type, if a type is
  genuinely unknown. If `any` is unavoidable, add a `// TODO: type this
  properly — reason` comment.
- Prefer `type` for unions/utility types, `interface` for object shapes that
  might be extended (e.g. repository contracts, entity shapes).

## Naming

- Files: `kebab-case.ts` (`product.service.ts`, `order.repository.ts`).
- Classes/Interfaces: `PascalCase` (`ProductService`, `IProductRepository`).
- Variables/functions: `camelCase`.
- Constants (truly constant, module-level): `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`.
- Booleans read as questions: `isActive`, `hasStock`, `canCheckout`.

## Linting & formatting

- ESLint + Prettier, enforced via a pre-commit hook (`husky` + `lint-staged`)
  and in CI — no formatting bikeshedding in PR review.
- Import order enforced: external packages → `server/shared/` → relative
  imports.

## Testing

- Unit tests colocated: `product.service.ts` → `product.service.test.ts`.
- Integration tests in `server/tests/integration`.
- Coverage target: meaningful coverage on services/repositories/utils, not a
  vanity percentage — don't write tests just to hit a number, but don't skip
  testing business logic either.
- Test naming: `describe('ProductService.getProduct', () => { it('throws
  NotFoundError when product does not exist', ...) })` — behavior-driven,
  not implementation-driven.

## Git

- Conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, `test:`, `chore:`,
  `docs:`, `perf:`.
- Branch naming: `feature/<short-desc>`, `fix/<short-desc>`,
  `chore/<short-desc>`.
- No direct commits to `main`; PRs require passing CI (lint, typecheck,
  test) before merge.
- Keep PRs scoped to one module/feature where possible — large
  cross-cutting refactors get their own PR with a clear description.

## Documentation

- Every module (`server/modules/product`, etc.) has a short `README.md` if
  its business rules are non-obvious (e.g. discount calculation, stock
  reservation during checkout).
- Public repository interfaces and service methods get a one-line JSDoc
  comment describing intent, not implementation.
